1. Introduction:

Music has stayed relatively constant in our lives, and it surrounds us during different moments. We use it to push us to the limits during an intense workout, help us focus while studying in the library till 2am, and we even use music to let loose while partying with our friends! During happy, sad, celebratory and other moments in our lives, music has stayed by our side.

On March 11, 2020, WHO (World Health Organization) declared COVID-19 a global pandemic. A majority of our lives changed from this point on such as switching to virtual school, following a stay at home order, closing down indoor seating in restaurants, wearing masks and staying 6 feet apart from friends. With such a huge change in our lives, we wanted to study the impact of COVID-19 on music, and see if the top 2020 songs had any distinct features compared to the top songs of 2010-2019. Since COVID-19 is still occurring in our lives today, we will be studying the top songs pre-COVID-19 and during/the peak of COVID-19.

Along with many new rules and changes to what our normal looked like, there was one app that started to change our lives as well. That app was TikTok. TikTok is an app where people can post 30 second to 1 minute videos about anything the user wants to post. We believe Tik Tok impacted the music/top songs of 2020 since many songs go viral if someone choreographs catchy dance moves to a portion of a song. This is how some artists become very popular and sometimes get discovered! One example is Doja Cats song Say So where she even included the catchy TikTok dance in her official music video. Along with our assumptions that TikTok played an important role for the top songs of 2020, we also want to analyze the features of popular TikTok songs.

What we will analyze:

  • Top Songs of 2010-2019 vs. Top Songs of 2020 (impact of COVID-19)
  • TikTok Songs vs Top Songs of 2020
  • What makes a song popular

2. Data Collection & Processing¶

Obtaining Data:
The top songs of 2020 data was obtained from Organize Your Music using this Spotify Tops Songs of 2020 Playlist. The top songs of 2010-2019 data were used from this Kaggle dataset. The top TikTok songs was also obtained from Organize Your Music, but using this Spotify Tik Tok Songs. The website Organize Your Music is super cool since it is linked to your Spotify account where you can analyze your own Spotify playlists. Moreover, you can find a specific Spotify playlists URI (heres a Spotify playlist to URI converter that helped us) and analyze that playlist, which is what we did. This website already produced the following properties for each song on the playlist.

  • Genre - the genre of the track
  • Year - the release year of the recording.
  • Added - the earliest date you added the track to your collection.
  • Beats Per Minute (BPM) - The tempo of the song.
  • Energy - The energy of a song - the higher the value, the more energetic. song
  • Danceability - The higher the value, the easier it is to dance to this song.
  • Loudness (dB) - The higher the value, the louder the song.
  • Liveness - The higher the value, the more likely the song is a live recording.
  • Valence - The higher the value, the more positive mood for the song.
  • Length - The duration of the song.
  • Acousticness - The higher the value the more acoustic the song is.
  • Speechiness - The higher the value the more spoken word the song contains.
  • Popularity - The higher the value the more popular the song is.

Tidying the Data:

The year added column of our data was not accurate since this date was the date I added the playlist to my Spotify account, so we removed this column. We also made sure all the column names for the datasets were the same. The dataset we first imported is the tops songs of 2010-2019, then we imported the top songs of 2020, and lastly we imported the top TikTok songs. We also created a dataset that combined the top songs of 2010-2019 and 2020, so we have a dataset that will carry the top songs of 2010-2020.

  • top_10s = top songs of 2010-2019
  • top_2020 = top songs of 2020
  • tiktok = the top Tik Tok songs
  • top_all = top songs of 2010-2020

3. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

3A: Visualizing Change in Track Properties from 2010 to 2020¶

First let's take a look at how the track properties we identified have changed in the top songs throughout the last decade using the Top Songs of 2010-2019 and the Top Songs of 2020. Because the data only provides the year each song was created, we'll take the average value for each track property for each year. Then we will create a line graph for each track property using our averages.

In [85]:
#find the average value of each track property for each year
top_decade = top_all.copy()

track_properties = ['bpm','nrgy', 'dnce', 'dB',
                     'live', 'val', 'dur', 'acous', 'spch']

property_avgs = top_decade.groupby(["year"])[track_properties].mean()
property_avgs.reset_index(inplace=True)

From this we can analyze the general trends of track properties during the 2010-2020 decade, giving us a larger scope that also reveals some of the impacts of COVID-19 on music popularity.

First, let's take a look at some of the track properties that trended downward over the past decade:

  • Energy - Energy progressively decre

  • Loudness (dB) - The higher the value, the louder the song.

  • Length - Song length has experienced a steady decline over the last decade, with top songs once averaging ~4 minutes droppting to average ~3 minutes.

Next, let's take a look at some of the track properties that trended upward over the past decade:

  • Danceability - The higher the value, the easier it is to dance to this song.

  • Acousticness - The higher the value the more acoustic the song is.

  • Speechiness - The steady increase of speechiness

  • Beats Per Minute (BPM) - The average tempo of top songs decreased from 2010-2019, but saw a sharp increase in 2020.

Finally, let's look at

  • Liveness - The higher the value, the more likely the song is a live recording.

To start comparing the track properties of the Top Songs of 2010-2019, the Top Songs of 2020, and the Top TikTok songs, we wanted to easily visulize this information. Thus, we decided to create violin plots of each track property and have each dataset side by side to see the similarities and differences! The 2010-2019 violin plot will be on the left, the TikTok dataset will be in the center, and the 2020 will be on the right side.

BPM: After plotting the violin plot for the Beats per Minute (BPM) of the 3 datasets, we can see that the mean for the 2010-2019, TikTok, and 2020 dataset are really similar. The 2010-2019 dataset has a larger range, and all the datasets has a large bulby part around the mean.

Energy: Surprisingly, the 2010-2019 had the highest mean for energy compared to TikTok and the 2020 datasets. We expected TikTok to have the highest energy average since we believed TikTok-ers dance to high energy music. Also it looks like the Top Songs of 2020 had the lowest average enery, which can mean that maybe because of COVID-19 people perferred to listen to low energy music.

Danceability: Another surprise is that the 2020 dataset had the highest average of dancebility, with TikTok dataset coming in close. The 2010-2019 dataset again had a large range compared to the other datasets. The 2020 dataset having the highest average for danceability is suprising since it had the lowest average for energy. It seems like people during COVID-19 listend to a lot of songs they can dance to. For all three datasets, the main bulby part is around the mean.

Loudness: Again, the 2010-2019 dataset had a large range. However, it looks like all three datasets have a really close average for loudness, and the main buly part of the plot is around the average.

Liveness: All three datasets have a large range for liveness, and similar averages. It looks like there were not too many songs in the datasets that were a live recording, sine the averages are around 10. The 2010-2019 dataset is more bimodal compared to the other two datasets.

Valence: Valance had a large range for all three datasets. Also, all the averages were similar for the three datasets. The 2010-2019 dataset is more unimodal than the other two datasets. The TikTok and 2020 datasets look the most similar and are slightly bimodal. It is surprising that the TikTok and 2020 dataset have the same average as the 2010-2019 dataset. We expected the songs in the TikTok and 2020 datasets to have a higher valence average since a higher valence correlates to a more positive mood. So we thought becuase of COVID-19 people would want to listen to songs with more positive moods. For TikTok we thought people would want to dance to music with positive moods.

Length: The range for the 2010-2019 dataset was the largest and also its mean was the highest compared to the other two datasets. For the 2020 dataset, the largest bulby part is lower than its average, so it seems like most of those songs are longer in length.

Acousticness The 2010-2019 dataset and TikTok dataset had similar ranges. The TikTok dataset looks more similar to the 2020 dataset since they have similar averages, but the 2020 dataset is more bimodal looking than the TikTok one. The average for the 2010-2019 dataset was lower than the other two datasets.

Speechiness: The averages for the TikTok and 2020 datasets were really similar, and the 2010-2019 dataset was a bit lower. All three datasets had a large range. The TikTok dataset looks pretty similar to the 2020 dataset.

Popularity: The popularity of the 2020 dataset looks the most different compared to the other two datasets. The 2020 dataset has a smaller range only between ~70 to ~95. The TikTok and 2010-2019 range is a lot bigger from 0 to 100. The average of the TikTok and 2010-2019 dataset is really close, while the average of the 2020 dataset is higher than the others. It seems like most songs in the TikTok dataset are around 80 (where the main bubly part is), however there is still a large amount of songs around 40 (the second main bubly part). The 2010-2019 data is unimodal. We expected that the TikTok songs would have a lot of popular songs, but instead it had a great range of songs of different popularities. The 2020 dataset had a lot of songs of high popular value.

3C: Finding Top Genres of Top Songs of 2010-2019, Top Songs of 2020, and Top TikTok Songs¶

The data from the top song of 2010-2019, 2020, and top TikTok songs contains a top genre column. We wanted to compare the genres of the 3 datasets and see what the most frequent genre is for each dataset and if there were any similarities. We were wondering if because of COVID-19 or TikTok that the top songs of 2020 most popular genre will be the same as the TikTok songs popular genre, or if it might be a different genre competely.

In [79]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from collections import Counter
%matplotlib inline

tiktok_df['top genre'].value_counts()

tiktok_df = tiktok_df['top genre'].value_counts().rename_axis('unique_values').reset_index(name='counts')

Lastly, we created a bar graph for the Top Songs of 2020 dataset's top genres and plotted it against it's frequency. Surprisingly, the most frequent genre was not Dance Pop, but rather Chicago Rap. We got curious why this was the most frequently showing genre in the Top Songs of 2020 Spotify playlist, and after a little more research we discovered that there were many Juice WRLD songs in this playlist, and most of his music's genre is Chicago Rap. Since Juice WRLD sadly passed away in 2020, his death was a huge topic in the media. His fans wanted to show their support and streamed his songs a lot that year, which allowed his songs to get in the Top Songs of 2020 playlist.

After plotting all the dataset's genres, we also noticed that many genres had similar names or variations of other genres. For example, there is a genre called "Pop Dance" as well as "Dance Pop". Moreover, some genre names can be too specific or too vauge. For example, Rihanna's music genre is called "Barbadian Pop" and the Jonas Brother's music genre is called "Boy Bands". Since the most frequent showing top genre for both the TikTok dataset and Top Songs of 2010-2019 dataset was Dance Pop, we wanted to see which dataset had more occurrances of the "pop" genre. In other words we wanted to see which dataset contained the most genres that contained the word "pop".

4. Hypothesis Testing¶

Different Track Properties vs. Popularity¶

Now, we will use scatter plots and multiple linear regession to test our hypothesis of whether or not track properties (specifically- tempo (bpm), energy, danceability, loudness (dB), liveness, valence, duration, acousticness, and speechiness) are significant in predicting a song's popularity.

To start out, we will plot each track property against song popularity for the songs between 2010 and 2020.

For the top songs from 2010 to 2020, we created scatter plots for each track property against Popularity. After creating the plots, we can see that there is likely little to no linear correlation between many track propoerties and Popularity. For example, for plots showing Loudness (dB) and Valence vs. Property, the same loudness correlates with a wide range of Popularity ratings, and a wide range of Valence values correlate with the same Popularity rating. However, for plots such as Danceability vs. Popularity, we can notice that on average, as the Danceability increases, the Popularity ratings also seem to increase. Additionally, for the plot of Duration and Energy vs. Popularity, as the Duration and Energy levels increase, on average, the Popularity ratings seem to decrease.

To analyze if this change is significant, we can run a multiple linear regression to find which track properties, if any, are significant in predicting the Popularity rating of a song. Our null hypothesis is that there is no relationship between other track properties of the table and Popularity, and our alternative hypothesis is that there is at least one track property variable that is significant in predicting song Popularity for songs from 2010 to 2020.

We can end backwards elimination here, as all variables have a p-value below 0.05. However, we must also note that the R-squared (0.088) and adjusted R-squared (0.083) values are still very low, so we know the model does not do well in explaining the extent of variation of song popularity against the remaining variables.

Additionally, the significant variables identified by the model are somewhat aligned with our predictions from the scatter plots-- we originally found that higher danceability is correlated with higher popularity and higher duration and energy are correlated with lower popularity. However, the model also found loudness (dB) to be a significant predictor of popularity, which we originally thought would not be predictor for a linear correlation. To examine this, we revisited the scatter plots, and we noticed that there is one outlier on the Loudness (dB) vs. Popularity graph that is at a very low dB and Popularity (whereas the rest are higher dB and a range of Popularity). Therefore, we believe this inclusion of dB in the final model may be due to the outlier.

Next, we will run the same models with scatter plots and multiple linear regression to test our original hypothesis on just the 2020 TikTok songs from our table.

From the summary output of the TikTok table after using Backwards Elimination, we notice that energy, loudness, valence, duration, and speechiness of songs are all significant predictors of 2020 TikTok song popularity (at a 95% confidence level). Although we were unable to notice such trends from the initial scatter plots, we have several hypotheses for why each predictor may be significant in a real-world context, as personal users of TikTok.

Firstly, higher valence may be linearly correlated with higher popularity, as valence is defined as the positiveness and happiness of a song. In the current environment with the COVID-19 pandemic, many users are likely to seek and benefit from songs that uplift their mood, therefore causing such songs to become more popular.

Secondly, a longer duration may be linearly correlated with higher popularity, as a longer song is more likely to have a variety of components that could become viral on the TikTok platform.

Thirdly, a higher speechiness duration may be linearly correlated with higher popularity, as more words in a song could lead to more inspirations for viral TikTok trends such as dances and lip syncs.

However, more data would be needed to support our hypotheses.

In addition, after researching the Spotify API, we found that there are 3 main categories of songs: Mood, Properties, and Context, that are a combination of the track properties we analyzed, as shown:

Mood: Danceability, Valence, Energy, Tempo

Properties: Loudness, Speechiness, Instrumentalness

Context: Liveness, Acousticness

From both the 2010-2020 and TikTok tables, we found that energy was a significant predictor. Additionally, danceability was a significant predictor of popularity for 2010 to 2020 music, and valence and was a significant predictor of popularity for TikTok music. Therefore, we know that on average, the Mood of songs are a significant contributor to the popularity levels.

Furthermore, loudness (dB) was a significant predictor in both tables and speechiness was a significant predictor in the TikTok table as well, so we can conclude that on average, the Spotify Properties of a song are also significant contributors to its popularity.
